tic and linguistic history of thinking -- tIV Semiotics of emotion -- t16 Semiotic conceptions of emotion -- t17 Multimodality, facial expression, and emotional language -- t18 Emotion and communication design -- t19 Emotion, colour, and language -- tV Grammatical dimensions of emotion research -- t20 Morphology and emotion -- t21 Interjections and other emotional communicative acts -- t22 Morphosyntactic structure and emotion -- tVI Semantics and the expression of emotion -- t23 Affective meaning in language -- t24 Vocabulary of emotions and its development in English, German and other languages -- t25 The use of emotion lexicon in emotion research -- t26 Emotions and figurative language -- t27 Studying emotion effects in language -- tVII Language action and the processing of emotion -- t28 Pragmatics and emotions in social contexts -- t29 Rhetoric, stylistics, and emotion -- t30 Deception and emotion -- t31 Apologies, forgiveness and the social perception of emotions -- t32 The pragmatics of emotion, argument and conflict0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Handbook consists of four major sections. Each section is introduced by a main article: Theories of Emotion – General Aspects Perspectives in Communication Theory, Semiotics, and Linguistics Perspectives on Language and Emotion in Cultural Studies Interdisciplinary and Applied Perspectives The first section presents interdisciplinary emotion theories relevant for the field of language and communication research, including the history of emotion research. The second section focuses on the full range of emotion-related aspects in linguistics, semiotics, and communication theories. The next section focuses on cultural studies and language and emotion; emotions in arts and literature, as well as research on emotion in literary studies; and media and emotion. The final section covers different domains, social practices, and applications, such as society, policy, diplomacy, economics and business communication, religion and emotional language, the domain of affective computing in human-machine interaction, and language and emotion research for language education. Overall, this Handbook represents a comprehensive overview in a rich, diverse compendium never before published in this particular domain.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLanguage and emotions. 4aAngewandte Linguistik. 4aEmotionsforschung. 4aKognition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLinguistic Emotion Research, Affective Sciences, Emotion and Cognition, Interdisciplinary Language and Emotion Research,.1 aAfacan, Şeyma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlm, Cecilia O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltarriba, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasnight-Brown, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkum, Jos J. A. van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonard, Constant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusse, Dietrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBąk, Halszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaffi, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin Ng, Bee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeonna, Julien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEatough, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoolen, Ad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForoni, Frances